    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it's still super hard to pin down. it feels so random, like something is just occasionally stepping in and cutting the line for no reason. i've looked at the throughput and bandwidth and nothing seems spiked. \n\nis there any way this could be related to something more low level, like packet corruption or some weird hardware-level instability in the AWS fabric? basically, anything that would cause a sudden, unexplained reset like that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It is quite rare for AWS infrastructure fabric to cause random, application-level \"Connection Reset by Peer\" errors without visible throttling or hardware alerts. Such sporadic behavior often suggests an intermediary component is timing out the connection due to inactivity or an aggressive keep-alive setting. You should verify if any firewalls or proxies *between* your EC2 and the remote peer might be enforcing idle timeouts. If all application and intermediary layers look clean, consider enabling more detailed packet tracing on the EC2 instance itself to look for TCP RST flags originating from the network stack.",
      "source": "target",
